content.description: The crux is getting onto the boulder.  Then working through the weathered top.
content.protection: Cams up to 4 (used for anchor).  Mostly hexes, nuts, and slings for the face climb.
content.location: Start on the left side wall as you enter the Bivy Cave.  N35° 52.894' W92° 54.751'    Climb up onto the boulder.

content.description: This is one of a group of new sport routes that have been bolted on Wall of Moderates. Very nice for beginner climbers.
content.protection: 5+ quick draws
content.location: 20 feet right of Three Beers (left angling crack with the tree).

content.description: Flared crack with big features on the surrounding wall.
content.protection: SR
content.location: Just a few feet left of the bivy cave.

content.description: This route sports the only bolt in the area.  You can use it or not.  There are plenty of trad options to the left.  The route features a small roof that is easily crested.
content.protection: Tree anchor.  I think I did the whole thing with passive pro.   Sometimes I'm just in awe of how perfectly the gear settles into the rock.   It can be a thing of beauty.
content.location: Look for the single bolt on a wall of trad.  To the right of The Highland.

content.description: Another beginner trad climber route.   Short.  Nothing memorable.
content.protection: Standard rack.  Nothing big.  There are 2 trees to anchor from.  The left tree looks very unhealthy.  Use the right tree.
content.location: 10 feet to the right of Outside World.   20 feet to the left of Balanced Mushroom Pillar.  Follows a dark water mark that stayed dry when other routes were wet.

content.description: Good route for a first trad lead. Lots of varied options for protection with big holds. This is the left angling crack with the tree growing out of it 1/2 up the wall.
content.protection: No anchors, tree on top.
content.location: This is in the middle of the featured wall left of the bivy cave.

content.description: Climb the "cheater boulder" which makes up the left wall of the far right passage to Bivy Cave.   Easier to get onto the face for taller climbers, but my 5'2" wife was able to make it.
content.protection: Large cams up to 4.    Hexagonals and nuts.
content.location: Between Bivy Cave and route #1 in the Cole Fennel book.   N35° 52.894' W92° 54.737'

content.description: Obvious crack/flake in the corner right of Nanda Devi.
content.protection: SR. Tree anchor.
content.location: Obvious crack/flake in the corner right of Nanda Devi.

content.description: Dihedral crack to right of bivy cave.    A little dirty at the tree anchor
content.protection: Tree anchor
content.location: Dihedral crack to right of bivy cave

content.description: This route starts at the dihedral of big fat burrito. Climb the slab and traverse left and up past the only bolt. Pull the roof to the left of the bolt and continue up and left to the anchors of unknown route near the arrette.
content.protection: SR to #3 and a few slings
content.location: Obvious flake dihedral is the start and continue up left to the point of the arrette. It starts at fat burrito and ends at the chains of adrift.

content.description: Short route.  Good beginner trad.
content.protection: Cams, nuts, and slings.   Tree anchor.
content.location: Look for the Balanced Mushroom Pillar.   This route starts 30 feet to the left and is in front of a nice tree.

content.description: Easy face climb using only hexes and tricams.  Tree anchor at the top.   Trees are small, so I used 2 of them.   Pull up your rope and rappel off a different tree closer to the edge.
content.protection: Hexes and tricams.  Sling some trees for an anchor.
content.location: Start on the far left of the boulders blocking the entrance to Bivy Cave.   Stand on top and place your first piece of gear.

content.description:
Cole Fennel calls this a two star 5.8. Perhaps I wasn't exactly on the line. It felt more like one star 5.6R to me.  

  Either way. Begin 10 ft right of Icy Corner and head for an obvious orange bulge and ledge. Rap down off a tree. 

  EDIT: No longer R. Retrobolted with 4 bolts and anchor.
content.protection:
Standard Rack and creativity. No anchors. 

  EDIT: Retrobolted with 4 bolts and anchor.
content.location: 10 feet right of the obvious Icy Corner

content.description: Start just left of Three Beers and climb straight up to end at the Three Beers topout. I'm sure I'm not the first one up this route. Easy climbing with a set of nuts and slings.
content.protection: Set of nuts and some slings. Tree anchor.
content.location: A few feet left of Three Beers (left angling crack with tree) that mergers with the top out of Three Beers.

content.description: 10 feet to the left of Adrift.   Dirty chicken heads on vertical wall.
content.protection: tree anchor.  May have been retro-bolted
content.location: 10 feet to left of Adrift

content.description: Fun jug bashing through the lower part and climb up and a bit left to a small vertical crux near the top. Top out to tree anchor.
content.protection: Sr to #2 and a sling.
content.location: The start is 10ft right of the arrette and top out left of obvious tree on top. Rap off of tree.

content.description: Climb through big chicken heads in the black streak leading to a thin crack in a short roof. Turning the roof presents an awkward but exciting crux.
content.protection: SR, slings for chicken heads, Tree anchor. There a bolt anchors you can rap from about 20 feet to the right of the top of the climb.
content.location: Pass Adrift and look for a short roof at the top of the wall with a thin crack. Look for the obvious black streak and chicken heads below.

content.description: A very fun, juggy arete. Would make an excellent first trad lead.
content.protection:
Standard Rack. No anchors. 

  EDIT: This route has been retrobolted and now has 5 bolts and an anchor.
content.location: When you approach Stack Rock, this is one of the first few routes on the left. See beta photo.

content.description: Beginner trad route.   Too short to be memorable.
content.protection: Standard rack. No large pieces.  Same tree anchor as Towards the Highland.
content.location: 10 feet to the left of Balanced Mushroom Pillar. Follows a dark water streak that stays dry when other routes are dripping.

content.description: Glide over a sea of chicken heads to reach the top
content.protection: Slings, cams, nuts.   Lots of choices.  Tree anchor
content.location: Around the corner to the right from Chicken Head Rodeo.

content.description: Follow juggy flake and then the path or least resistance.
content.protection: tree anchor
content.location: Between Jaguars and Mothballs.   Juggy flake

content.description: You could do this whole route with just slings - hence the name.  Yea Ha!
content.protection: Slings, cams, nuts - whatever you are in the mood to use.  Tree anchor
content.location: Between Sailing alone and Highland.  Start at the R of the detached boulder.  Basically the same starting location as Sugar High Pink Cowgirl, but turn 90 degrees to the right.    N35° 52.894' W92° 54.737'

content.description:
Climb up easy slab to a small roof.  Pull over the roof and climb up a jug ladder to the anchors.  Briefly wanders out to the arete near the top but moves back right to get to the anchors. 

  Whoever put up this route, feel free to reach out to me to update the route details.
content.protection: 4 bolts plus 2 bolt anchor with quick links
content.location: Far left route on main face of Moderate Wall.  Starts on slab under the small roof about 5 feet right of corner.

content.description: The crux is in the middle of the route
content.protection: Bolts, anchors on top.
content.location: Just to the left of Six Pack

content.description: Climb slab for 5 feet to small roof crux protected by one bolt, then cruise on chicken heads using horizontal cracks for pro and make a slightly steeper finish to the anchors.
content.protection: Standard rack, one bolt, and bolt anchor.
content.location: About 10 feet right of Adrift arete and where a single bolt is on a roof.

content.description: Begin on the blunt arete. Follow the obvious left angling crack towards the top.
content.protection: Standard Rack. Bolted anchor with quick links.
content.location: Find the obvious arete of Icy Corner. This is the next arete to the left.

content.description:
A collection of moderate trad lines, often with inconspicuous pro in horizontal cracks. There are no bolted anchors, but there are some convenient rappel trees. 

  EDIT: Most of these routes have been retrobolted and anchors have been added.
